# Deploying cert-manager with Helm

This guide walks through deploying cert-manager on Kubernetes using the official Helm chart, including configuring a Cloudflare DNS-01 `ClusterIssuer` and requesting certificates for internal hostnames.

## Prerequisites

- A running Kubernetes cluster
- `kubectl` configured to talk to your cluster
- Helm installed (`brew install helm` or see [helm.sh](https://helm.sh))
- A domain hosted on Cloudflare
- A Cloudflare API token with DNS edit permissions scoped to your zone

## Add the cert-manager Helm Repository

```bash\
helm repo add jetstack https://charts.jetstack.io
helm repo update
```

## Install cert-manager

cert-manager requires its Custom Resource Definitions (CRDs) to be installed before the controller. The `--set crds.enabled=true` flag handles this automatically:

```bash
helm install cert-manager jetstack/cert-manager \
  --namespace cert-manager \
  --create-namespace \
  --set crds.enabled=true
```

Verify the installation is healthy before proceeding:

```bash
kubectl get pods -n cert-manager
```

All three pods (`cert-manager`, `cert-manager-cainjector`, and `cert-manager-webhook`) should be in the `Running` state.

---

## Configure Secrets

cert-manager needs access to your Cloudflare API token to create and delete DNS TXT records during DNS-01 challenges. Store this as a Kubernetes Secret in the `cert-manager` namespace.

> **Important:** Never commit this file to version control. Add it to `.gitignore` immediately.

```yaml
# issuer-secrets.yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: Secret
metadata:
  name: cloudflare-credentials
  namespace: cert-manager
type: Opaque
stringData:
  api-token: YOUR-CLOUDFLARE-API-TOKEN
```

> **Note:** Using `stringData` instead of `data` allows you to store the value as plaintext — Kubernetes will base64-encode it automatically on apply. If you use `data` instead, you must base64-encode the value yourself: `echo -n "your-token" | base64`.

Apply the secrets file:

```bash
kubectl apply -f issuer-secrets.yaml
```

---

## Configure the ClusterIssuer

A `ClusterIssuer` is a cluster-scoped resource that defines how cert-manager requests certificates. Unlike a namespaced `Issuer`, a `ClusterIssuer` can serve certificate requests from any namespace in the cluster.

> **Note:** `ClusterIssuer` can only reference Secrets in the `cert-manager` namespace, regardless of where the `Certificate` resource itself is created.

```yaml
# cloudflare-dns-issuer.yaml
apiVersion: cert-manager.io/v1
kind: ClusterIssuer
metadata:
  name: cloudflare-dns-issuer
spec:
  acme:
    # Your email address for Let's Encrypt account registration and expiry notices.
    email: YOUR-EMAIL@YOUR-DOMAIN.COM
    server: https://acme-v02.api.letsencrypt.org/directory
    privateKeySecretRef:
      # cert-manager will create this Secret automatically to store your
      # Let's Encrypt account private key.
      name: letsencrypt-account-key
    solvers:
      - dns01:
          cloudflare:
            apiTokenSecretRef:
              name: cloudflare-credentials
              key: api-token
        selector:
          # Restrict this solver to domains under your zone.
          # Remove the selector block to use this issuer for all domains.
          dnsZones:
            - YOUR-DOMAIN.COM
```

> **Note:** The `email` field under `acme` is a plain string and does not support referencing a Secret. It is used by Let's Encrypt for account registration and expiry notices only, not as a credential.

Apply the issuer:

```bash
kubectl apply -f cloudflare-dns-issuer.yaml
```

Verify the issuer is ready:

```bash
kubectl describe clusterissuer cloudflare-dns-issuer
```

The `Status` section should show `Ready: True`. If it does not, check the cert-manager logs:

```bash
kubectl logs -n cert-manager deployment/cert-manager -f
```

